"""More paraphrases for previously-short / -ambiguous queries that may have missed retrieval."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is RAG?','Retrieval-Augmented Generation. LLM augmented with external knowledge fetched at query time. Pipeline: user query → search relevant docs in vector DB → include docs in prompt → LLM answers grounded in retrieved context. Pros: cites sources, knowledge update without retrain, less hallucination, smaller model OK. Cons: pipeline complexity, retrieval quality bounds answer quality.'),
    ('What is chunking in RAG?','Splitting documents into chunks that fit in LLM context + are semantically coherent. Strategies: fixed size (~500-1000 tokens), sentence-boundary, paragraph-boundary, semantic (recursive splitter), hierarchical (parent doc + chunk). Overlap (~10-20%) helps preserve context across boundaries. Poor chunking is the #1 cause of bad RAG quality.'),
    ('What is the difference between authentication and authorization?','Authentication = WHO you are (password, biometric, token). Authorization = WHAT you can do (RBAC, ACL, policies). Common bug: checking auth but not authz — user can call API but accidentally accesses other users\' data. Always check BOTH on every protected endpoint. Modern: RBAC + ABAC for fine-grained policies.'),
    ('What does git pull do?','Combines git fetch + git merge (or rebase if configured). Downloads remote refs and integrates them into your current branch. Default merge can create unnecessary merge commits; `git pull --rebase` keeps history linear. Safer alternative: `git fetch` first, review, then `git merge` or `git rebase` deliberately.'),
    ('What does git commit do?','Records staged changes (git add) as a new entry in the repo history. Each commit has: hash (SHA), author, timestamp, message, parent(s), tree of files. Local until pushed. `git commit -m "msg"` to inline message; bare `git commit` opens editor. `git commit --amend` modifies the latest commit (never amend after push to shared branch).'),
    ('What is a closure?','Function that captures variables from its enclosing scope, accessible even after that scope returns. JS: `function makeCounter() { let n = 0; return () => ++n; }`. Python: nested function referencing outer var. Use for: factory functions, private state, callbacks that need context. Memory note: closures keep referenced vars alive — can leak if forgotten.'),
    ('What is a thread?','Lightweight unit of execution sharing a process\'s memory + open files. Cheap to create vs processes. Communicates with other threads via shared variables (with locks) or message passing. Trade-off: shared mutable state = race conditions. Modern alternative: async coroutines (single-threaded, cooperative) for I/O-bound work.'),
    ('What is an API?','Application Programming Interface — contract specifying how software components interact. Common types: REST API (HTTP + JSON), GraphQL, gRPC, library API (function signatures), OS API (syscalls). Good APIs: consistent, minimal, predictable, well-documented, backward-compatible. Bad APIs: bite users for years.'),
    ('What is JSON?','JavaScript Object Notation. Text format for structured data. Six types: string, number, boolean, null, object ({key: value}), array ([...]). Lingua franca of web APIs. Parsed by every language. Caveats: no comments (in strict JSON), no trailing commas, dates serialize as strings, big ints lose precision in JS. Alternatives: YAML (more human-friendly), Protobuf (binary, smaller, typed).'),
    ('What is HTTP?','Hypertext Transfer Protocol. Request-response protocol over TCP (HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2) or UDP (HTTP/3 via QUIC). Stateless: each request independent. Methods: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE. Headers + body + status code (200, 404, 500, etc.). Foundation of the web + most APIs. HTTPS = HTTP + TLS encryption.'),
    ('What is SQL?','Structured Query Language. Standard for relational databases. Read: SELECT cols FROM table WHERE cond GROUP BY col ORDER BY col. Write: INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE. Schema: CREATE TABLE, ALTER TABLE. Joins: INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL. Implementations vary slightly across dbs (Postgres, MySQL, SQLite, SQL Server). The most enduring data language since the 1970s.'),
    ('What is Git?','Distributed version control system by Linus Torvalds. Tracks file changes over time. Each clone is a full copy with history. Workflows: feature branches, pull requests, rebase vs merge. Most code in the world managed by Git. Common hosts: GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket. Powerful but command line can be intimidating — GUIs help.'),
    ('What is Docker?','Containerization platform. Package app + dependencies + OS bits into an "image"; run as a "container" (isolated process). Same image runs anywhere Docker runs. Replaced "works on my machine" with "ship the machine." Docker Compose for multi-container apps locally; Kubernetes for production orchestration. Containerd is now the actual runtime underneath.'),
    ('What is Linux?','Open-source Unix-like operating system kernel. Powers ~90% of servers, all Android phones, supercomputers, embedded devices. Distributions (Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, RHEL, Arch) bundle the kernel + userland + packages. Familiarity is core skill for backend dev / DevOps. Free, open source, controlled by Linus + community.'),
    ('What is a function?','Reusable named block of code that takes inputs (parameters) + returns output (return value, or none). Encapsulates logic, prevents duplication, makes code testable. Pure function: output depends only on inputs, no side effects. Modern style: small focused functions (do one thing well) composed into larger logic.'),
    ('What is a class?','Blueprint for creating objects. Bundles data (attributes) + behavior (methods). Instances share class structure but have own attribute values. Supports inheritance (subclass extends parent), polymorphism (override methods), encapsulation (hide internals). Modern advice: favor composition over inheritance. Some languages (Rust, Go) avoid classes entirely in favor of structs + traits/interfaces.'),
    ('What is recursion?','Function that calls itself with a smaller subproblem until reaching a base case. Use for: tree/graph traversal, divide-and-conquer, problems with self-similar structure. Watch for: clear base case, progress toward base case, stack depth limits. Some problems naturally recursive (tree walks); others naturally iterative (loops over arrays).'),
    ('What is an iterator?','Object that produces values one at a time. Implements __next__ (Python) / Symbol.iterator (JS) / Iterator trait (Rust). Lazy: only produce when asked, save memory for huge sequences. Underlies for-loops, generators, streams. Doesn\'t support random access (no indexing) — use a list/array for that.'),
    ('What is a generator?','Function with `yield` that produces values lazily. Each call advances to the next yield, pausing in between. Saves memory for large/infinite sequences. Python: `def gen(): yield 1; yield 2`. Use with: for-loop, list(), sum(), itertools pipelines. Don\'t store state across yields — variables persist between yields naturally.'),
    ('What is a lambda?','Anonymous function literal. Python: `lambda x: x*2`. JS: `(x) => x*2`. Rust: `|x| x*2`. Most useful for: callbacks, key= args to sort, short transformations in map/filter/reduce. Limited to single expression in Python; modern langs allow multi-line. Don\'t abuse — named functions are clearer for non-trivial logic.'),
    ('What is async/await?','Syntactic sugar over promises/futures. `async function f() { const x = await otherPromise; return x; }`. await pauses until promise settles, returning value or throwing on rejection. async functions ALWAYS return Promises (JS) / coroutines (Python). Combined with parallel-await (Promise.all / asyncio.gather) for concurrent ops.'),
    ('What is a hash map?','Same as hash table. Key-value store with O(1) average get/put. Implementation: array of buckets, hash function picks bucket. Collisions handled by chaining or open addressing. Pythonic: dict. Java: HashMap. JS: Map (or plain Object). Use whenever you need fast lookup by key.'),
    ('What is a stack data structure?','LIFO (Last In First Out) collection. Operations: push (add to top), pop (remove from top). Use for: function call frames, undo, backtracking, parsing, DFS, evaluating expressions. Implementations: list (Python), array (any language), or linked list. Stack-overflow when recursion too deep = limited call stack size.'),
    ('What is a queue data structure?','FIFO (First In First Out) collection. Operations: enqueue (add to back), dequeue (remove from front). Use for: BFS, task processing, event handling, IPC. Python: collections.deque (fast both ends) or asyncio.Queue. Don\'t use list (pop(0) is O(n)). Distributed queues: RabbitMQ, Kafka, SQS.'),
    ('What is a linked list?','Sequence where each element points to the next. Insert/delete at known node: O(1). Random access: O(n) (must walk from head). Singly-linked (one direction) vs doubly-linked (both). Less cache-friendly than arrays (scattered in memory). Modern advice: prefer arrays/vectors unless you actually need cheap mid-list insertions.'),
    ('What is Big O notation?','Asymptotic upper bound on algorithm growth. O(1) constant, O(log n) logarithmic, O(n) linear, O(n log n), O(n²) quadratic, O(2^n) exponential. Ignores constants + low-order terms. Tells you how it scales, not absolute speed (small n can have O(n²) beat O(n log n) due to constants). Mental model: how does cost grow if I 10x the input?'),
]
